const post = {
 title: 'Welder Uniforms: FR Shirts, Leather Layers, and What Actually Holds Up',
 description:
 'Welders need NFPA 2112 FR base layers, leather welding jackets or sleeves over the top, and decoration that doesn\'t void the rating. Here\'s the actual spec — the FR base shirts, the leather over-layer system, and how to brand FR welding garments without compromising compliance.',
 category: 'Compliance',
 readTime: '9 min read',
 date: 'May 9, 2026',
 isoDate: '2026-05-09',
 image: '/images/generated/kit-electrical.jpg',
 slug: 'welder-uniforms-fr-shirts-las-vegas',
}

const faqs = [
 { q: 'What do welders wear?', a: 'A typical welder runs three layers: an NFPA 2112-rated FR base shirt (Bulwark Excel-FR or Carhartt FR Lightweight), heavy leather welding jacket or sleeves over the top to block spatter and slag, and FR-rated leather gloves and boots. The FR base shirt protects against flash-fire; the leather over-layer handles direct welding hazards.' },
 { q: 'Can FR shirts replace leather welding jackets?', a: 'No. FR shirts protect against thermal events (flash fire, arc flash) but they\'re not designed for the direct contact hazards of welding — molten metal spatter, slag, and grinding sparks. Leather welding jackets and sleeves block those direct hazards. The two layers serve different protective purposes and welders use both.' },
 { q: 'What FR rating do welders need?', a: 'NFPA 2112 is the standard for flash-fire protection in industrial environments where flammable materials may be present. For arc welding without other process hazards, the leather over-layer is the primary PPE. For welders working in oil, gas, or process environments, NFPA 2112 + 70E dual-rated FR base layers cover both flash-fire and arc-flash exposure in a single garment.' },
 { q: 'Can you embroider company logos on FR welding shirts?', a: 'Yes — using FR-compatible Nomex (aramid) thread that retains the protective rating through industrial laundering. Standard polyester thread melts in arc and flash-fire events and voids the certification. Decoration follows the FR garment manufacturer\'s placement rules (chest, sleeve, no oversized back logos that change the protective fabric area).' },
 { q: 'How do you brand a leather welding jacket?', a: 'Custom embroidered or sewn-on patches stitched directly to the leather using FR-rated Nomex thread. The patches are decorated separately on cotton-blend or twill fabric, then sewn into place — the leather itself isn\'t embroidered. Heat-applied decoration is not used on welding leather because the heat process can compromise the fire protection of the leather itself.' },
 { q: 'What FR brands are best for welders?', a: 'Bulwark Excel-FR ComforTouch (industry standard, dual NFPA 70E + 2112), Carhartt FR Lightweight (popular with crews who reject heavier FR), Wrangler Riggs FR (button-down styling for crews who want a "regular work shirt" look). All three are dual-rated for flash-fire and arc-flash, all three accept FR-safe decoration.' },
 { q: 'Do welders working at heights need different gear?', a: 'Yes — ironworker welders walking iron need ANSI 107 Class 2 hi-vis on top of the FR layer for crane and signal-person visibility. The combination of FR + hi-vis is challenging because most hi-vis fabric isn\'t FR-rated; specialty FR Hi-Vis garments (Bulwark JLR8, Carhartt FR Hi-Vis Class 3) solve this with a single dual-compliant layer.' },
]

